{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489183","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489183"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:08:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:08:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"610"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"610","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/610"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.55,0.05,0.11,0.23,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"610"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87336"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"610","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/610"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"610"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71593"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"479"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"1704"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1303"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1984"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30000"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87336","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/87336"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of eight kg weight loss, upper abdominal discomfort and poor appetite. His wife noted yellowing of his eyes over the past week. He has a medical history of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease and hypertension, for which he takes salbutamol and amlodipine. He has a 40 pack-year smoking history and drinks six cans of beer daily. An abdominal ultrasound from 12 months ago showed a cirrhotic liver. His blood tests reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAlanine transferase 100 U/L (\u003C55)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAspartate transferase 250 U/L (\u003C45)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EGamma-glutamyl transferase 600 U/L (\u003C60)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAlkaline phosphatase 180 U/L (30-110)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EBilirubin 55 \u00b5mol/L (2-24)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHaemoglobin 95 g/L (115-155)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EInternational normalised ratio 1.4 (0.9-1.2)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations is the most appropriate next step?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Contrast-enhanced CT scan","Viral hepatitis serology","Serum albumin","Alpha-fetoprotein","Thiamine level"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features concerning for hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC) in the context of established cirrhosis. The most appropriate next investigation is a \u003Cstrong\u003Econtrast-enhanced CT scan\u003C/strong\u003E to evaluate for liver lesions. Modern imaging techniques are the cornerstone of HCC diagnosis, with CT, MRI, or contrast-enhanced ultrasound being the primary diagnostic tools.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlpha-fetoprotein\u003C/strong\u003E was historically used for HCC diagnosis but is now considered less reliable due to poor sensitivity and specificity. Up to 40% of early HCCs may have normal AFP levels. It is more commonly used for monitoring disease progression or response to treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EViral hepatitis serology\u003C/strong\u003E would be useful to determine the underlying cause of liver disease but is not the immediate priority when HCC is suspected. This information would not change the immediate management plan.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum albumin\u003C/strong\u003E measurement would provide additional information about liver synthetic function but would not assist in establishing the diagnosis of HCC.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThiamine level\u003C/strong\u003E may be relevant given the patient\u0027s alcohol use but is not the priority given the clinical suspicion of HCC.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHCC typically develops in patients with chronic liver disease, particularly those with cirrhosis. The non-specific symptoms of weight loss, abdominal discomfort, and jaundice, combined with deranged liver function tests in a patient with known cirrhosis, make HCC a likely diagnosis requiring urgent investigation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Hepatocellular carcinoma commonly presents with non-specific symptoms including weight loss, abdominal pain and anorexia.","Contrast-enhanced imaging is the primary diagnostic tool for hepatocellular carcinoma.","Regular surveillance for hepatocellular carcinoma is essential in patients with cirrhosis."],"references":["Heimbach JK, Kulik LM, Finn RS, Sirlin CB, Abecassis MM, Roberts LR, et al. AASLD guidelines for the treatment of hepatocellular carcinoma. Hepatology. 2018;67(1):358-80.","Lok AS, Sterling RK, Everhart JE, Wright EC, Hoefs JC, Di Bisceglie AM, et al. Des-gamma-carboxy prothrombin and alpha-fetoprotein as biomarkers for the early detection of hepatocellular carcinoma. Gastroenterology. 2010;138(2):493-502.","Marrero JA, Feng Z, Wang Y, Nguyen MH, Befeler AS, Roberts LR, et al. Alpha-fetoprotein, des-gamma carboxyprothrombin, and lectin-bound alpha-fetoprotein in early hepatocellular carcinoma. Gastroenterology. 2009;137(1):110-8.","Marrero JA, Kulik LM, Sirlin CB, Zhu AX, Finn RS, Abecassis MM, et al. Diagnosis, Staging, and Management of Hepatocellular Carcinoma: 2018 Practice Guidance by the American Association for the Study of Liver Diseases. Hepatology. 2018;68(2):723-50."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71593"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"610"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71593","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/71593"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-27T14:44:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-27T14:46:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"610"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87336"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data"